# C++ DataModel & ServerModel Architecture — Engineering Prompt

## Overview

You are building a cross-platform C++ application targeting **Windows** (Win32/MSVC or MinGW) and **Android** (NDK/CMake). The architecture is a **hierarchical DataModel** system inspired by Roblox's engine, combined with a **ServerModel** that bridges to a remote multiplayer backend via HTTP. Below is every layer explained with implementation details.

---

## 1. DataModel Pointer

The `DataModel` is the **root singleton** of your engine. It owns all top-level services via `std::shared_ptr` and is accessed globally through a raw or smart pointer.

```cpp
// DataModel.hpp
#pragma once
#include <memory>
#include <string>
#include <unordered_map>

class Instance;
class Game;
class Players;
class ExampleService;

class DataModel {
public:
    static DataModel* Get();          // Singleton accessor
    void Init();
    void Destroy();

    std::shared_ptr<Game>          game;
    std::shared_ptr<Players>       players;
    std::shared_ptr<ExampleService> exampleService;

private:
    static DataModel* s_instance;
    DataModel() = default;
};
```

```cpp
// DataModel.cpp
#include "DataModel.hpp"
#include "Game.hpp"
#include "Players.hpp"
#include "ExampleService.hpp"

DataModel* DataModel::s_instance = nullptr;

DataModel* DataModel::Get() {
    if (!s_instance) s_instance = new DataModel();
    return s_instance;
}

void DataModel::Init() {
    game          = std::make_shared<Game>();
    players       = std::make_shared<Players>();
    exampleService = std::make_shared<ExampleService>();
}
```

**Usage:**
```cpp
DataModel* DM = DataModel::Get();
DM->Init();
DM->players->AddPlayer("Player1");
```

